API and the rest of the pipeline — when geocoding returns no results for an address, the service needs to skip it and continue with the remaining stops. I can mock the geocoding module to return \"no results\" for a specific address, but the real test is whether the service properly wires the geocoding failure into the skip-and-continue logic and passes the filtered addresses to the optimizer. This requires the geocoding module and service orchestration to work together.\n\nMinimum level: **Integration**\n\n. A unit test with a mocked geocoding dependency could work if the service exposes a single function like `geocode_and_optimize(addresses)` that accepts a mocked geocoding call, but the behavior is fundamentally about how the service orchestrates the flow across modules — geocoding, filtering, and optimization — so the cross-module wiring is what matters.\n\nFor behavior 5, I'm looking at whether duplicate addresses get consolidated into a single stop. If deduplication is based on string matching, that's a straightforward unit test of the deduplication function itself, but if it requires geocoding to detect duplicates by coordinates, then the integration between geocoding and deduplication becomes the critical part.\n\nThe behavior description mentions \"duplicate addresses in the input list,\" which points to string-level matching before geocoding happens. So I'm leaning toward **Unit** — the failure mode is really about whether the deduplication algorithm works correctly, not about how modules interact. Though I should note this could shift to Integration if the actual implementation detects duplicates post-geocoding instead.\n\nLet me think through this more carefully: the question is whether I'm testing the deduplication function in isolation or verifying the end-to-end flow where deduplicated stops feed into the optimizer. If I can call the deduplication function directly with duplicate addresses and confirm it returns a single consolidated stop, that's a Unit test. The optimizer receiving that one stop versus two is a separate concern. I'll go with **Unit** since the core behavior can be verified at the function level.\n\nNow I'm settling on my test classifications: TSP heuristic quality, time window estimation, and shift-hours validation are all Unit tests, while geocoding failure handling needs Integration testing. For the probability distributions, I'm assigning high Unit confidence to the logic-based tests and lower Integration percentages, with minimal System and Agentic involvement across the board.\n\nAssigning probabilities now...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9659,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9659},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b38e87e7-193a-4a4e-96e6-1b10240c11af","uuid":"3d08e009-b47d-4823-9114-d10c2205cdee"}
